            I'll use the data_processing_validator tool to validate the fetched data against a schema. Since we need a schema but don't have one specified, I'll use a default schema for JSON data.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator {
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array"
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {}
}</tool_call>

I'll use the data_processing_transformer tool to convert the JSON data to XML format before validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer {
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "xml"
}</tool_call>

            Since the transformer expects JSON input but failed, I'll first parse the raw API response using the data_processing_parser tool to ensure proper JSON formatting before conversion.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser {
  "source": "data/input.json"
}</tool_call>

Now that we have properly parsed JSON data, I'll attempt the format conversion to XML again with the data_processing_transformer tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer {
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "xml"
}</tool_call>

            Now that we have the data in XML format, I'll retry the validation using the data_processing_validator tool with the XML schema.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator {
  "schema": {
    "xs:schema": {
      "xmlns:xs": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema",
      "elementFormDefault": "qualified"
    }
  },
  "data": {}
}</tool_call>
